problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in mathematics would. Evaluate $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$.
gpt_response:
To evaluate the expression $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60}$, we can combine the terms under a single cube root. We have:

$\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60} = \sqrt[3]{12\times 20\times 15\times 60}$

Simplifying the product under the cube root gives:

$\sqrt[3]{12\times 20\times 15\times 60} = \sqrt[3]{12\times 20\times 15\times 60} = \sqrt[3]{21600}$

Now, we find the cube root of 21600, which is  280. Therefore, $\sqrt[3]{12}\times \sqrt[3]{20}\times \sqrt[3]{15}\times \sqrt[3]{60} = 280$.
